## 2. Gender Inequality in Education

### 2.1 Disparities in Access and Quality

Globally, girls face significant barriers to education due to gender discrimination. According to Save the Children, 132 million girls are out of school worldwide, with girls in conflict-affected areas being 2.5 times more likely to be out of school than boys ([Save the Children, 2023](https://www.savethechildren.org/us/what-we-do/gender-equality)). Social norms often prioritize boys’ education over girls’, expecting girls to undertake household chores or marry early, limiting their schooling opportunities.

Even when girls attend school, they frequently receive lower-quality education and less support, as seen in studies from Bangladesh and Malawi where girls were perceived as less capable and their education deemed less valuable ([Chisamya et al., 2012](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijedudev.2011.10.004)). This discrimination perpetuates educational inequalities and reduces girls’ future economic and social prospects.

### 2.2 Impact on Boys

Boys are also affected by gender norms in education, often pressured to conform to ideals of masculinity that discourage academic engagement. For example, boys may face stigma for excelling in subjects or activities considered feminine, leading to disengagement or dropout. Additionally, the shortage of male teachers in many countries can deprive boys of positive role models, potentially impacting their motivation and behavior in school ([Jamieson, 2005](https://www.oise.utoronto.ca/fieldcentres/sites/www.oise.utoronto.ca.fieldcentres/files/resources/where-have-all-the-male-teachers-gone.pdf)).

